Step 1: What is a Normal Method?
class Dog
  def bark
    "woof"
  end
end

Now:

dog = Dog.new
dog.bark

Ruby:

Looks inside Dog

Finds bark

Runs it

Simple.

Step 2: What If Method Does NOT Exist?
dog.run

There is no run.

Ruby says:

NoMethodError

But before raising error…

Ruby secretly checks:

“Does this class have something called method_missing?”

That’s it.

That’s the whole entry point.

Step 3: What is method_missing?

It is just a normal method with a special name.

class Dog
  def method_missing(name, *args)
    puts "You tried to call #{name}"
  end
end

Now:

dog = Dog.new
dog.run

Output:

You tried to call run

That’s it.

Nothing magical.

So What Is Happening?

When Ruby cannot find a method:

Instead of directly throwing error,

It calls:

method_missing(method_name, arguments)

You can decide what to do.

That’s all.

Why Would Anyone Use This?

Imagine:

You want this:

user.find_by_name
user.find_by_email
user.find_by_age

You don’t want to manually write:

def find_by_name; end
def find_by_email; end
def find_by_age; end

Instead you say:

“If method starts with find_by_, handle it.”

That’s where method_missing is useful.

Now define_method (Even Simpler)

Forget everything.

Look at this:

class Cat
end

Now later I do:

Cat.define_method(:meow) do
  "meowww"
end

Now:

cat = Cat.new
cat.meow

It works.

We created method at runtime.

That’s it.

Difference in Very Simple Words

method_missing:
👉 Waits until method is called
👉 Then handles it

define_method:
👉 Creates method in advance
👉 Then Ruby finds it normally

Real Life Analogy

method_missing:

You go to shop.
Item not on shelf.
Shopkeeper says: “Tell me what you want, I’ll try to arrange.”

define_method:

Shopkeeper already prepared the items and placed them properly.

